We start by noting that the denominator is in the form

\begin{align*}\displaystyle{}a^2-x^2\end{align*}

with \emph{a = 5}. This is a good indicator that we want to do a trig
substitution with

\begin{align*}\displaystyle{}x=a\sin\theta\end{align*}

because

\begin{align*}\displaystyle{}a^2\sin^2\theta+a^2\cos^2\theta=a^2\end{align*}

and hence

\begin{align*}\displaystyle{} a^2 - a^2\sin^2\theta = a^2\cos^2\theta\end{align*}

We will use this identity to handle the square root in the denominator.
So, let

\begin{align*}
x&=5\sin\theta\\
dx&=5\cos \theta d\theta.\end{align*}

We must also modify the limits of integration since we have a new
variable. When

\begin{align*}
x&=0=5\sin\theta\end{align*}

solving for $\theta$ gives $\displaystyle {}\theta=0$. Solving

\begin{align*}
x&=5/2=5\sin\theta\end{align*}

for $\theta$ gives $\displaystyle {}\theta=\frac{\pi}{6}$. Substituting
these values into our integral we obtain

\begin{align*}\int_{0}^{5/2}\frac{dx}{\sqrt{25-x^{2}}} = \int_{0}^{\pi/6}\frac{5\cos \theta d\theta }{\sqrt{25-(5\sin\theta)^{2}}} = \int_{0}^{\pi/6}\frac{5\cos \theta d\theta }{\sqrt{(5)^2-(5)^2(\sin\theta)^{2}}}.\end{align*}

We can use the identity above we get

\begin{align*}\int_{0}^{\pi/6}\frac{5\cos \theta d\theta }{\sqrt{(5)^2-(5)^2(\sin\theta)^{2}}} = \int_{0}^{\pi/6}\frac{5\cos \theta d\theta }{\sqrt{(5)^2(\cos\theta)^{2}}} = \int_{0}^{\pi/6} 1 d\theta = \frac{\pi}{6}\end{align*}

Since this is a definite integral, the result is a number and we do not
need to return to the previous variables.
